STATEMENT OF OPERATING CONDITIONS
3.2. Request for Transportation or Storage Service
1. Any interested, prospective Shipper shall submit a request for transportation or storage service (Request) in writing to Cranberry on a Request Form supplied by Cranberry. Cranberry will time and date stamp each Request Form on the date Cranberry receives the completed Request Form. Cranberry shall evaluate and respond to such Request as soon as reasonably possible after receipt of such Request. A Request shall be considered acceptable and valid only if the information specified in the Request is provided completely in writing (including, without limitation, information showing the creditworthiness of the prospective Shipper), but Cranberry, on a non- discriminatory basis, may waive all or a portion of such information in individual instances when the information is already in possession of Cranberry. Requests for service shall be sent to:
Cranberry Pipeline Corporation PO Box 4544 Houston, Texas 77077-4544 Attn: Mr. James S. Jameson Phone: 281-589-4903 Fax: 281-589-4613
2. Form of Request for Transportation or Storage Service
(a) Valid Request - Each Request, to be considered as an acceptable and valid request, must furnish all of the information set forth below on the Request Form.
(b) Requestor's Identification
i. Name, address, and telephone number of party requesting service.
ii. The affiliation to shipper, if any, of the party requesting service from Cranberry
(c) Shipper's Identification
(Note: the "shipper" is the party proposing to execute the Agreement.)
i. Name, address, and telephone number of Shipper(s).
ii. Nature of the Shipper(s) business (i.e., an interstate pipeline, intrastate pipeline, local distribution company, end-user, producer, or marketer).
iii. State in which Shipper is organized or incorporated.
iv. The affiliation, if any, of the Shipper(s) with Cranberry.
v. The "on behalf of" entity, if applicable.
(d) Type of Service Requested
Specify whether desired service is firm or interruptible storage service or interruptible system-wide transportation.
(e) Quantity (stated in MMBtu's)
i. Maximum Daily Transportation Quantity (MDTQ) to be transported.
ii. Maximum Daily Receipt Point(s) Volume (MDV) to be transported by Receipt Point(s). The sum of the MDV's must equal the MDTQ.
iii. The MDV at each Delivery Point(s). The sum of the Delivery point(s) MDV's must equal the MDTQ.
iv. Total quantity of gas requested to be transported over the life of the Agreement, defined as the MDTQ times the number of days of the initial term.
v. Total Annual Storage Quantity (TASQ).
vi. Maximum Daily Injection Quantity (MDIQ) and Maximum Daily Withdrawal Quantity (MDWQ).
(f) Receipt Point(s)
Location of Receipt Point(s) and the name of the party that will supply the gas at each Receipt Point described.
(g) Delivery Point(s)
Location of Delivery Point(s) and the name of the party which will receive the gas at each Delivery Point described.
(h) Certified Statement
A Certified Statement that the Shipper has, or will have by the time of the execution of an Agreement with Cranberry, title to the gas or right to deliver the gas which is to be transported and owns facilities or has contractual rights which will cause such gas to be delivered to and received from Cranberry.
(i) Term of Service
i. Date service is requested to commence.
ii. Date service is requested to terminate.
(j) Source/use of Gas
i. Whether the supplier of the gas to be transported is affiliated with Cranberry and, if so, the extent of such affiliation (if known).
ii. The producing area of the gas requested to be transported.
A copy of a Request Form is available by contacting Cranberry at the above address and phone number.
3. Valid Execution - Shipper(s)' Request shall be considered null and void if Cranberry has tendered an Agreement for execution to Shipper and Shipper fails to execute the Agreement within thirty (30) days thereafter.
4. Shipper's Performance - If a Shipper that has executed an Agreement fails, on the later of (i) the date service is to commence, or (ii) sixty (60) days after the Shipper executes the Agreement, to nominate a quantity for gas for transportation or storage, or fails, having nominated a quantity of gas and Cranberry having scheduled the quantity for transportation or storage, to tender such gas for transportation or storage on the date it is scheduled, Cranberry may terminate the Shipper's Agreement and the Shipper's Request shall be deemed null and void.
CRANBERRY PIPELINE CORPORATION Section 3.2 FERC NGPA GAS TARIFF SOC - REQUEST FOR TRANSPORTATION ORIGINAL VOLUME NO. 1 OR STORAGE SERVICE Version 0.0.0
Issued on: October 8, 2010

STATEMENT OF OPERATING CONDITIONS
3.1. Services
Subject to the other provisions of this Operating Statement, Cranberry shall provide the following services on a not unduly discriminatory, open-access basis on its West Virginia intrastate pipeline system for any customer desiring such services (Shipper): (a) interruptible, system-wide interstate transportation service pursuant to Section 311 of the NGPA; (b) firm and interruptible stand-alone interstate storage service pursuant to Section 311 of the NGPA at its X-1 Storage Field and Raleigh Storage Field. In order to qualify for any of the foregoing services, a prospective Shipper must execute a Transportation Agreement or Storage Agreement (Agreement) to be provided to Shipper by Cranberry. The Agreement shall identify the term, the Receipt Points and Delivery Points, the minimum and maximum contracted quantities, the applicable rates and charges, and other applicable terms and conditions of service. In the event there is a conflict between the terms and conditions of an Agreement and this Operating Statement, the terms and conditions of this Operating Statement shall prevail.
CRANBERRY PIPELINE CORPORATION Section 3.1 FERC NGPA GAS TARIFF SOC - SERVICES ORIGINAL VOLUME NO. 1 Version 0.0.0
Issued on: October 8, 2010

STATEMENT OF OPERATING CONDITIONS
3.4. Service Priority
Transportation and storage service shall be provided on a first-come, first-served basis, which shall be based on the date of receipt by Cranberry of Shipper's completed written Request as provided in Section 3.2. Upon the execution of a transportation or storage service agreement, a shipper's service priority will be established as follows:
a. Firm storage service agreements shall have the highest priority of service.
b. Interruptible transportation and interruptible storage service agreements shall have the next highest priority of service; provided that interruptible transportation service associated with injections or withdrawals of gas pursuant to a shipper's firm storage agreement shall be accorded a higher service priority than other interruptible transportation service.

Issued on: October 8, 2010

STATEMENT OF OPERATING CONDITIONS
3.3. Availability of Capacity
1. Capacity availability in Cranberry's system shall be determined on a not unduly discriminatory basis by Cranberry, it being recognized that the capacity in Cranberry's pipeline system varies from area to area and from day to day based upon a number of factors.
2. Cranberry shall have no obligation to construct, modify, improve, repair, or alter any facilities in order to provide service requested by any Shipper or prospective Shipper. However, if a Shipper requests new or additional transportation or storage service and Cranberry is agreeable to providing the requested service, it will do so on the following terms, unless otherwise agreed to in writing, on a not unduly discriminatory basis:
(a) If Cranberry agrees to construct and operate lateral pipelines (if applicable), metering and regulating facilities that include electronic measurement and data communication equipment (if applicable) and/or new and/or additional Delivery Point(s) to such Shipper or Receipt Point(s) from such Shipper (if applicable): (1) the metering and regulating facilities shall be installed at such point(s) which, in Cranberry's reasonable judgment, is the most practical, convenient and readily accessible location, (2) the lateral pipeline (if any) shall be installed by use of not less than a nominal four-inch (4") diameter pipe; (3) the Shipper will provide all exhibits necessary to support the proposed service for any needed regulatory proceedings; and (4) the Shipper will contribute an aid-to-construction amount to Cranberry which is equal to the cost of the additional facilities, including all costs involved in filing any applications, pursuing said approvals, and in obtaining all licenses and permits required for the services or construction and, further, amounts necessary to reimburse any costs, including any income taxes that may be incurred by Cranberry as a result of the contribution. Cranberry will construct, own and operate any facilities so constructed.
(b) Shippers, whether new or existing, shall bear and pay all costs and expenses attributable to the construction of any lateral pipelines or expansions of existing lateral pipelines prior to the commencement of such work. Nothing in this section shall require Cranberry to file an application for a certificate of public convenience and necessity under Section 7(c) of the Natural Gas Act.
(c) On a not unduly discriminatory basis, Cranberry may agree to pay for all or part of the cost incurred by Cranberry for the modification or construction of taps, valves, measurement equipment, lateral, or other facilities required at Receipt or Delivery Point(s) to effectuate the receipt from, or delivery to, Shipper of natural gas, as requested hereunder, when the construction or modification of such facilities is economically beneficial to Cranberry.
For the purposes of determining whether a project to receive or deliver gas for Shipper is economically beneficial to Cranberry, Cranberry will evaluate each prospective project, on a not unduly discriminatory basis, based upon, among other criteria, the cost of the facilities to be constructed for such Shipper by Cranberry, the incremental operating and maintenance expenses and/or administrative and general expenses which would be attributable to the facilities, and the revenues which Cranberry estimates will be generated as a result of constructing and/or modifying such facilities.

3.16. Waivers
1. Cranberry may waive any of its rights hereunder or any obligations of Shipper as to any specific default that has already occurred, or case-by-case in advance as to any specific, temporary operational problem, on a basis that is not unduly discriminatory.
2. Notwithstanding the foregoing, no waiver by either Cranberry or Shipper of any one or more defaults by the other in performance of any of the provisions of an effective Agreement shall operate or be construed as a waiver of any other existing or future default or defaults, whether of a like or of a different character.
3. All requests for waivers pursuant to Section 3.16 shall be in writing. All responses to requests for waivers shall be in writing and served on all of Cranberry's then current Shippers.

STATEMENT OF OPERATING CONDITIONS
3.12. Creditworthiness
Cranberry shall not be required to perform or to continue to perform service on behalf of any Shipper who is or has become insolvent, or who, after Cranberry's request, fails within two (2) days to demonstrate, in Cranberry's sole reasonable determination, the ability to pay all anticipated transportation and/or storage charges when due; provided, however, that Shipper may receive service if Shipper pre-pays for such service or furnishes good and sufficient security, as determined by Cranberry in its reasonable discretion, in an amount equal to the cost of performing the service requested by Shipper for a three-month period, such prepayment amount to be determined by multiplying the Shipper's MDQ by the number of days in such three month period multiplied by the currently prevailing transportation and/or storage rates as calculated on a one hundred percent (100%) load factor basis.

STATEMENT OF OPERATING CONDITIONS
3.11. Nominations and Scheduling
A Shipper must submit in writing its daily nominations (in Dth) for each Agreement at least ten (10) business days prior to the beginning of the month on which the service is to take place. Each nomination must specify the Receipt Point(s) and Delivery Point(s) quantities, which may not exceed the maximum daily volume (MDV) established for each point. The sums of the Receipt Point(s) MDVs and the sums of the Delivery Point(s) MDVs may not exceed the maximum daily transportation quantity (MDTQ) or maximum daily storage quantity (MDSQ) established for each Agreement. In order to change any daily nomination, a Shipper must provide at least twenty-four (24) hours written notice prior to 8a.m. on the day in which transportation service is to take place. Mid-month nomination changes are subject to Sections 3.13 or 3.14, as applicable.

STATEMENT OF OPERATING CONDITIONS
3.13. Interruptible Transportation Services
1. Cranberry is not required to provide any requested transportation service: (a) for which capacity is not available; or (b) would require the construction or acquisition of any new facilities by Cranberry.
2. Service rendered shall be: (a) not be subject to curtailment, interruption, or discontinuance except as provided herein or in Section 3.8 of this Operating Statement; or (b) pursuant to Section 3.13.7, interruptible and subject to curtailment or interruption in the event that Cranberry, in its sole judgment, determines that as a result of operating conditions, it cannot honor on any day or portion thereof its firm service obligations without curtailing or interrupting interruptible service.
3. The executed Agreement shall set forth the MDTQ applicable to Shipper's service hereunder.
4. Unless Cranberry and Shipper mutually agree otherwise, the minimum monthly bill that Shipper shall pay for transportation service shall be the transportation charge and any other applicable charges.
5. The executed Agreement shall specify the Receipt Point(s) for quantities tendered by Shipper for transportation hereunder. For any day when Shipper desires Cranberry to transport gas for its account, it shall nominate to Cranberry pursuant to Section 3.11, specifying the quantity of gas it desires to have transported on such day. When Shipper's nominations are scheduled and confirmed, Cranberry shall transport the quantity of gas so nominated, subject to the limitations set forth in this Section 3.13.
6. On and after the first day of any month, the advance notice given to Cranberry for change in nominations on any given day during a month must be at least twenty-four (24) hours prior to 8 a.m. on the day in which transportation is to take place.
7. A Shipper with an executed Interruptible Transportation Service Agreement may request Cranberry to provide interruptible transportation service to deliver gas to Shipper on any day. Cranberry shall provide such transportation, unless Cranberry issues an operational flow order, or, in Cranberry's sole judgment, such transportation cannot be provided without adverse effect upon deliveries to firm shippers or to Cranberry's other operations, including, without limitation, Cranberry's firm storage obligations.
CRANBERRY PIPELINE CORPORATION Section 3.13 FERC NGPA GAS TARIFF SOC - INTERRUPTIBLE TRANSPORTATION SERVICES ORIGINAL VOLUME NO. 1 Version 0.0.0
Issued on: October 8, 2010

STATEMENT OF OPERATING CONDITIONS
3.15. Operational Flow Orders
1. Cranberry will operate its system in a reasonable manner, based upon conditions known to or forecast by Cranberry at the time, maintaining line pack, scheduling maintenance, maintaining and testing storage inventories, coordinating receipts and deliveries, and issuing operational flow orders ("OFOs") as needed to maintain system reliability and provide services to its shippers.
2. Once an operational flow order has been issued, Cranberry will cooperate with the affected Shippers to accomplish the results intended by the OFO. So long as Cranberry acts reasonably and in good faith, Cranberry shall not be held liable for any damages whatsoever suffered by Shipper or by any third party.
3. Description and Contents of OFOs.
1. An OFO shall be an announcement by Cranberry that:
a. will advise Shipper of operating conditions which may affect its services; examples include, but are not limited to, circumstances where operating constraints preclude or limit storage injections or withdrawals; or
b. will direct a Shipper or class of Shippers to take specific action; examples include but are not limited to OFOs directing a Shipper to limit hourly takes and OFOs directing Shippers to deliver specific quantities to Cranberry at specific Receipt Points.
2. Each OFO shall contain the following information:
a. time and date of issuance;
b. time that OFO is effective;
c. duration of OFO (if none is specified, the OFO will remain effective until further notice);
d. the Shipper(s) or class of Shippers affected by the OFO;
e. the action, if any, that Shipper(s) must take; and
f. any other information required by the terms of this Operating Statement.
4. Any failure by a Shipper to comply with an OFO shall subject such Shipper to an OFO penalty in the amount of $25.00 per Dth, which penalty shall be assessed on the quantities of gas that a Shipper is in violation of the applicable OFO, including, without limitation, gas quantities in excess of limitations placed on a Shipper's receipts or deliveries, and gas quantities which a Shipper fails to deliver to or receive from Cranberry's facilities.
CRANBERRY PIPELINE CORPORATION Section 3.15 FERC NGPA GAS TARIFF SOC - OPERATIONAL FLOW ORDERS ORIGINAL VOLUME NO. 1 Version 0.0.0

STATEMENT OF OPERATING CONDITIONS
3.14. Firm and Interruptible Storage Services
1. Cranberry is not required to provide any requested storage service or associated transportation service: (a) for which capacity is not available; or (b) would require the construction or acquisition of any new facilities by Cranberry.
2. Service rendered shall either be: (a) firm and shall not be subject to curtailment, interruption, or discontinuance except as provided herein or in Section 3.8 of this Operating Statement; or (b) pursuant to Section 3.14.14, interruptible and subject to curtailment or interruption in the event that Cranberry, in its sole judgment, determines that as a result of operating conditions, it cannot honor on any day or portion thereof its firm storage service obligations without curtailing or interrupting interruptible storage service.
3. The executed Agreement shall set forth the Total Annual Storage Quantity ("TASQ"), Maximum Daily Injection Quantity ("MDIQ"), and Maximum Daily Withdrawal Quantity ("MDWQ") applicable to Shipper's service hereunder. The storage injection season shall commence on May 1st of each year and run through October 31st of each year, and the storage withdrawal season shall commence November 1st each year and run through April 30th of each year.
4. Unless Cranberry and Shipper mutually agree otherwise, the minimum monthly bill that Shipper shall pay for service shall be the reservation charge and any other applicable charges.
5. The executed Agreement shall specify the Receipt Point(s) for quantities tendered by Shipper for storage injection hereunder. For any day when Shipper desires Cranberry to store gas for its account, it shall nominate to Cranberry pursuant to Section 3.11, specifying the quantity of gas it desires to have injected into storage on such day. When Shipper's nominations are scheduled and confirmed, Cranberry shall inject into storage for Shipper's account on such day, the quantity of gas so nominated, subject to the limitations set forth in this Section 3.14.
6. On and after the first day of any month, the advance notice given to Cranberry for a change in injections on any given day during a month must be at least twenty-four (24) hours. Cranberry may waive any part of the twenty-four (24) hours of notice upon written request of Shipper if, in Cranberry's sole reasonable judgment, operating conditions permit such waiver.
7. The maximum quantity of gas which Shipper shall be entitled to tender to Cranberry for injection into storage on any one day shall be 1/140 of Shipper's TASQ, unless force majeure or other operational reasons prevent such injection quantity, in whole or in part, for a particular day(s).
8. The executed Agreement shall specify the Delivery Point(s) for all quantities to be withdrawn from storage.
9. For any day when Shipper desires Cranberry to withdraw gas for its account, it shall nominate to Cranberry in accordance with Section 3.11 or Section 3.14.10, as applicable, specifying the quantity of gas it desires to have withdrawn from storage on such day. When Shipper's scheduled nominations are confirmed, Cranberry shall withdraw from storage for Shipper's account on such day, the quantity of gas so nominated, subject to the limitations set forth in this Section 3.14.
10. On and after the first day of any month, the advance notice given to Cranberry for a change in withdrawals on any given day during a month must be at least twenty-four (24) hours. Cranberry may waive any part of the twenty-four (24) hours of notice upon written request of Shipper if, in Cranberry sole reasonable judgment, operating conditions permit such waiver.
11. The initial maximum quantity of gas which Shipper shall be entitled to request Cranberry to withdraw from storage on any one day shall be determined by Cranberry based on: (a) the total quantity of gas injected into each storage field (X-1 and Raleigh) by all shippers by November 1st of each year; and (2) the application of the attached pro forma withdrawal curves for each field (X-1 and Raleigh) to such total quantity in each field. Cranberry shall Inform each Shipper no later than five (5) days prior to the end of each month during the ensuing withdrawal season of the actual maximum daily withdrawals for that shipper for the following month based on the withdrawals of all shippers for the then-current month (e.g. Cranberry would inform each Shipper by November 25th of each Shipper's December maximum daily withdrawals based on the total November withdrawals).
12. The maximum quantity of gas which Shipper shall be entitled to request Cranberry to store shall be determined by Cranberry based on the total gas quantities to be stored by Shipper and other shippers and the operational characteristics of the storage field(s) as solely determined by Cranberry. Shipper shall be entitled to inject interstate gas into both the X-1 and Raleigh Fields, unless operating conditions or force majeure prevent such injections during any day(s) during the storage injection season.
13. Unless otherwise agreed to in writing by Cranberry, Shipper must withdraw ninety percent (90%) of its TASQ by the end of each storage year (April 30th). In the event that a Shipper fails to withdraw ninety percent (90%) of its TASQ, Shipper shall be charged a $1.00 per Dth penalty for all remaining gas in storage. All penalty revenues collected by Cranberry shall be distributed on a pro rata basis (calculated on each Shipper's TASQ) to all Shippers receiving Storage service for the storage year in question to the extent such Shipper(s) are not responsible for the penalties generating such revenues. Such penalty revenue shall be distributed within sixty (60) days after the end of the calendar year in question.
14. A Shipper may request Cranberry to provide interruptible storage service to deliver gas to Shipper on any day. Cranberry shall make such delivery if such gas is available from Shipper's storage gas balance, unless Cranberry issues an operational flow order, or, in Cranberry's sole judgment, such delivery cannot be made without adverse effect upon deliveries to other shippers or to Cranberry's other operations, including, without limitation, Cranberry's other storage and/or transportation obligations.
CRANBERRY PIPELINE CORPORATION Section 3.14 FERC NGPA GAS TARIFF SOC - FIRM AND INTERRUPTIBLE ORIGINAL VOLUME NO. 1 STORAGE SERVICE Version 0.0.0
Issued on: October 8, 2010

STATEMENT OF OPERATING CONDITIONS
3.10. Monthly Balancing
It is the responsibility of the Shipper to balance its receipts and deliveries on a monthly basis. A Shipper may avoid the application of the monthly imbalance cash-out process by adjusting its service nominations during the month to reduce imbalances to within acceptable tolerance levels as described herein. Imbalances which are not corrected by the end of the month will be eliminated after the close of the month in accordance with the following procedures:
(a) If the imbalance existing at the end of the month is within the 10% tolerance, the imbalance will not be subject to cash-out, and instead will be carried forward into the following month for in-kind resolution through the Customer's adjustment of its nominations in the subsequent month. Cranberry will notify Customers of any imbalance between its receipts and deliveries under any Service Agreement by the ninth business day following the close of each month
(b) In the event a Shipper's monthly quantity of gas supplied at the Receipt Point(s) under its Agreement is less than the monthly quantity of gas transported and delivered by Cranberry to the Delivery Point(s) under Shipper's Agreement by an amount in excess of the 10% tolerance (the "Deficiency Quantity") then Shipper shall pay to Cranberry, in addition to all applicable transportation charges, a cash-out amount fee based on the percentage of the Deficiency Quantity to the actual monthly quantity. The cash-out will only be applied to portion of the imbalance that exceeds the 10% tolerance limit. For Deficiency Quantity percentages in excess of 10%, the fee will be the higher of: (1) 110% of the daily average during the month of deliveries of the Midpoint price published in Platts Gas Daily, Daily Price survey for Columbia Gas, Appalachia, or (2) 110% of the first-of-the-month Index price published in Platt's Inside FERC's Gas Market Report for Columbia Gas Transmission Corp., multiplied by the Deficiency Quantity. For Deficiency Quantity percentages greater than 15%, the fee will be the higher of: (i) 125% of the daily average during the month of deliveries of the Midpoint price published in Platts Gas Daily, Daily Price survey for Columbia Gas, Appalachia, or (ii) 125% of the first-of-the-month Index price published in Platt's Inside FERC's Gas Market Report for Columbia Gas Transmission Corp., multiplied by the Deficiency Quantity.
(c) In the event a Shipper's monthly quantity of gas supplied at the Receipt Point(s) under its Agreement is greater than the monthly quantity of gas transported and delivered by Cranberry to the Delivery Point(s) under Shipper's Agreement by an amount in excess of the 10% tolerance (the "Excess Quantity"), then Shipper shall cash-out the excess by selling to Cranberry such Excess Quantity at price based on the percentage of the Excess Quantity to the actual monthly quantity. The cash-out will only be applied to portion of the imbalance that exceeds the 10% tolerance limit. For Excess Quantity percentages in excess of 10% the price will be the lesser of: (1) 90% of the daily average during the month of deliveries of the Midpoint price published in Platts Gas Daily, Daily Price survey for Columbia Gas, Appalachia, or (2) 90% of the first-of-the-month Index price published in Platt's Inside FERC's Gas Market Report for Columbia Gas Transmission Corp., multiplied by the Excess Quantity. For Excess Quantity percentages greater than 15%, the price will be the lesser of: (i) 75% of the daily average during the month of deliveries of the Midpoint price published in Platts Gas Daily, Daily Price survey for Columbia Gas, Appalachia, or (ii) 75% of the first-of-the-month Index price published in Platt's Inside FERC's Gas Market Report for Columbia Gas Transmission Corp., multiplied by the Excess Quantity.
(d) No imbalance cash-outs will be applied against Shippers for imbalances which are the result of force majeure, compliance with operational flow orders, or other operational conditions caused solely by Cranberry. No imbalance cash-outs will be applied when a prior period adjustment applied to the current period causes or increases a current month penalty.
(e) Cranberry will determine monthly imbalances on the basis of the Shipper's Service Agreements. When a single Shipper has multiple interruptible Service Agreements and imbalances exist under one or more of those Service Agreements for the month served, Cranberry will net the offsetting imbalances against each other to arrive at the aggregate imbalance for the Shipper.

The percentage of gas so provided shall be determined from time-to-time by Cranberry based on the fuel used or lost and unaccounted for percentage(s) approved by the Commission.

STATEMENT OF OPERATING CONDITIONS
3.17 Force Majeure 1. If either Cranberry or Shipper is rendered unable, wholly or in part, by force majeure, to perform its obligations under this Agreement, other than the obligation to make payments then or thereafter due, it is agreed that performance of the respective obligations of Cranberry or Shipper to deliver, transport and store gas, so far as they are affected by force majeure, shall be suspended from the inception of any such inability until it is corrected but for no longer period. The party claiming such inability shall give notice thereof to the other party as soon as practicable after the occurrence of the force majeure. If such notice is first given by telephone or radio communication, it shall be confirmed promptly in writing giving full particulars. The party claiming such inability shall promptly correct such inability to the extent it may be corrected through the exercise of reasonable diligence.
2.
